Which Product should I add??¶

In order to help the Vendor in the process of adding competetive products, we can propose 2 simultaneous solutions:

1) Suggesting the most successful products from other similar vendors¶

In this scenario we will need to find "similar" products based on product name and description. We can imagine an application, where once the vendor decide the location it can serve, we propose automatically the list of top 10 successful products from other vendors in that location.

2) Demand Prediction¶

We can assist the vendor in the processing of adding new items, by predicting the amount of orders to expect over the next 30 days. We can imagine a ML model updating the demand prediction in real-time while the vendor documents the new products in the app :) We can gamify the process and let the vendor maximize its expected score by improving the product name or description for example.

What will this notebook cover?¶

  • Data loading and exploratory data analysis
  • Cleaning of data: removing non-english products, clean text (removing stopwords/digits, lemmatization, ...)
  • Clustering of similar products
  • Proposing top 10 successful products from similar vendors

class FastTextLanguageDetector:
    
    def __init__(self, model_path: str):
        """
        Init
        
        :param model_path: the path to the pretrained model
        """
        self.fmodel = fasttext.load_model(FASTTEXT_PATH_MODEL)
        
    def detect_language(self, text: str):
        """
        Detectcts the language of the text
        
        :param text: input text to detect the model
        :return: (str) detected language, e.g. "en", "fr", "hu"
        """
        x = text.replace("\n", " ")
        lang_tmp, _ = self.fmodel.predict(x)
        lang = lang_tmp[0].split("__")[-1]
        return lang
    
lang_detector = FastTextLanguageDetector(FASTTEXT_PATH_MODEL)

Warning : `load_model` does not return WordVectorModel or SupervisedModel any more, but a `FastText` object which is very similar.

Cleaning Textual data & Getting Pretrained DocVectors¶

In order to run the clustering alogorithm, we have to first decide on how the data should be represented. There are 2 known baselines of representing sentences/documents for the purpose of clustering:

  • tf-idf + LSA (i.e. TruncatedSVD in sklearn)
  • doc2vec

In this notebook we test the pretrained doc2vec approach. Where basically a product given its name and description will be represented by a vector, such that 2 products with similar names and descriptions should be close to each other in the mapping matrix.

One easy way of obtaining a vector for a product/docm would be to take the average of all word2vec embeddings matched in the product name and description.

The textual data needs to be pre-processed and cleaned before building the document vectors. One can apply basline pre-processing steps:

  • put text in lower case
  • remove all english stopwords
  • tokenize the text
  • remove all non alpha tokens
  • Lemmatize the tokens
In [20]:
class EnglishTextProcessor:
    nlp = en_core_web_sm.load()
    lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()
    english_stopwords = set(stopwords.words("english"))

    def preprocess_text(self, text: str):
        """
        Cleans the text with basic operations:
        - put string to lower
        - removes punctuation
        - removes digits
        - removes stopwords
        - lemmatizes the remaining clean tokens

        :param text: the text to preprocess
        :return: clean text
        """
        word_tokens_lemmas = []
        if text:
            x = text.lower() # lower
            word_tokens = word_tokenize(x) # tokenize words
            word_tokens_lemmas = [
                self.lemmatizer.lemmatize(el) for el in word_tokens
                if el not in self.english_stopwords and el.isalpha()
            ] # remove stop-words, non-alpha tokens, lemmatize
        return word_tokens_lemmas
    
    def word_vectors(self, text: str):
        """
        Gets word vectors from spacy pretrained model
        :param text: the text to process
        :return: (numpy.array) the average of word vector
        """
        doc = self.nlp(text)
        return doc.vector
    
    def process_text_vectorize(self, text: str):
        """
        Cleans the text and sends back the doc vector
        the doc vector is simply the average of all Token vectors in the Doc
        
        :param text: the text to process
        :return: (dict) the lemmatized tokens and corresponding word tokens
        """
        tokens = self.preprocess_text(text)
        vectors = self.word_vectors(" ".join(tokens))
        
        return {
            "lemmatized_tokens": tokens,
            "doc_vector": vectors,
        }

Clustering of similar products¶

There are many algorithms possible to run the clustering and many preprocessing steps as well. In this notebook, we would like to evoke 2 famous ones: K-Means and HDBSCAN.

K-Means: The simplest/baseline algorithm. One needs to spcify the number of clusters, and that is always a tough part ... In this exercise, the expected number of clusters is not given ... K-Means has some limitations: it tends to work at best when clusters are spherical, equally sized, equally dense, most dense in the center of the sphere, not contaminated by noise/outliers. That is very rarely the case in reality ...

HDBSCAN: In HDBSCAN we do not need to specify the number of clusters. It uses density-based approach which makes few implicit assumptions about the clusters. It is a non-parametric method that looks for a cluster hierarchy. Rather than looking for clusters with a particular shape, it looks for regions of the data that are denser than the surrounding space.

In this notebook, we decide to use HDBSCAN. For speed purposes we will run the clustering on a reduced dimensionnal embeddings using UMAP. This will also be easier to visualize.

Reduce Dimension to 3D with UMAP¶

In [24]:
%%time
X = np.stack(df_menus_f["doc_vector"].values)
reducer = umap.UMAP(n_components=3, metric='cosine', random_state=42).fit(X)
embedding = reducer.transform(X)

CPU times: user 18.3 s, sys: 193 ms, total: 18.5 s
Wall time: 16.6 s

Train HDBSCAN¶

In [25]:
%%time
clusterer = hdbscan.HDBSCAN()
clusterer.fit(embedding)
df_menus_f["vendor_type_cluster"] = clusterer.labels_

CPU times: user 345 ms, sys: 3.17 ms, total: 348 ms
Wall time: 347 ms

Let's Join the cluster Id to the product table¶

Now have vendors joined into clusters. For a given user we can simply look at the top 10 products proposed by other vendors from same cluster :)

In [29]:
df_en_f = df_en.merge(df_menus_f)
processor = EnglishTextProcessor()
In [30]:
class NewItemsRecommender:
    def __init__(self, df_cluster, text_processor):
        """
        Init
        
        :param df_cluster: table with products and vendors clustered
        :param text_processor: the NLP text processor
        """
        self.df_cluster = df_cluster
        self.text_processor = text_processor
        
    def top10_products_to_consider(self, vendor_id: int, n_top_p: int):
        """
        Proposes the top 10 products to consider to add with buzz words/ingredients in the name/description
        
        :param vendor_id: the vendor_id
        :param n_top_p: the top N products to show from similar vendors
        """
        try:
            cluster_id = self.df_cluster.loc[self.df_cluster.vendor_id == vendor_id].iloc[0]["vendor_type_cluster"]

            products_similar_vendors = self.df_cluster.loc[
                (self.df_cluster.vendor_type_cluster == cluster_id) & (self.df_cluster.vendor_id != vendor_id)]

            products_similar_vendors = products_similar_vendors.sort_values("order_count", ascending=False).drop_duplicates(["vendor_id", "product_name"]).iloc[:n_top_p]

            output = []
            for el in products_similar_vendors.iterrows():
                row = el[-1]
                product_name_keywords = self.text_processor.preprocess_text(row["product_name"])
                description_name_keywords = self.text_processor.preprocess_text(row["product_description"])
                location = row["vendor_geohash"]
                output.append({
                    "product_name_keywords": product_name_keywords,
                    "description_name_keywords": description_name_keywords,
                    "recommended_location": location,
                })
            
            return output
        except Exception:
            raise

recommender = NewItemsRecommender(df_en_f, processor)
